{
  "message": "fuzz: add replay::Recording::from_bytes target for .war binary format (ft-p2bjm)\n\nExercises crates/frankenterm-core/src/replay.rs:128 (Recording::from_bytes)\nand the internal frame-header state machine at :36 (parse_frame) under\nadversarial byte sequences. Oversize input is already bounded by the\n256 MiB cap added in 3a0cac70; this harness fuzzes the sub-cap parser\nitself where frame-length arithmetic, unknown-frame-type skipping,\nand duration-delta rewinds are the residual risks.\n\nAttack surface: any command that opens a user-supplied recording path\n(`ft replay load`, session restore, CI-fed fixtures). Oracle is\nno-panic / no-allocation-explosion \u2014 libfuzzer handles the timeout\ncase for infinite-loop regressions.\n\nTarget + corpus seeds:\n- fuzz/fuzz_targets/replay_recording_from_bytes.rs: per-input length\n  gate at 8 MiB to keep iteration cost bounded (far above realistic\n  header + multi-frame shapes, below the 256 MiB enforcement cap).\n- fuzz/corpus/replay_recording_from_bytes/ seeded with:\n  - empty (zero-length input)\n  - huge_payload_len (malformed header claiming oversize payload)\n  - multi_frame_marker_output (stacked frames, realistic shape)\n  - single_output_1byte (minimal valid body)\n  - truncated_header (len byte present, no payload bytes)\n  - unknown_frame_type (forces the skip path at parse_frame:36)\n  - zero_duration_resize (resize frame with zero delta)\n\nfuzz/Cargo.toml: flip default features to [core-fuzz-targets] so\n`cargo +nightly fuzz run replay_recording_from_bytes` works without\npassing --features on every invocation. The feature itself still\nexists; only the default is enabled, matching how the core targets\nare actually run in practice.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>",
